        <!-- Tips -->
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: var(--accent-color);">Tipping Tips</h2>
        <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
                <h3>Quick Mental Math</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>For 20%: move the decimal one place left (10%) and double it — e.g., $65 bill → $6.50 → $13 tip</li>
                    <li>For 15%: calculate 10% and add half — e.g., $80 bill → $8 + $4 = $12 tip</li>
                    <li>For 25%: divide the bill by 4 — e.g., $60 bill → $15 tip</li>
                    <li>Round up your total to a whole dollar for easier math and a slightly more generous tip</li>
                    <li>When in doubt, 20% is the safe default for any sit-down service in the US</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
                <h3>Tipping Etiquette</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Always tip on the pre-tax subtotal, not the total including sales tax</li>
                    <li>Check if gratuity is already included — common for large parties (6+) at restaurants</li>
                    <li>Tip in cash when possible — servers often receive cash tips immediately without processing delays</li>
                    <li>Don't penalize the server for kitchen issues like food quality or wait times — those aren't their fault</li>
                    <li>International travelers: tipping customs vary widely — research local norms before traveling abroad</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SEO Content -->
        <div class="seo-content">
            <h2>How to Calculate a Tip</h2>
            <p>Calculating a <strong>tip</strong> (also called a <strong>gratuity</strong>) is simple: multiply the bill amount by the tip percentage expressed as a decimal. For example, a 20% tip on a $50 bill is $50 × 0.20 = $10. Add the tip to the original bill to get the total: $50 + $10 = $60. If splitting among multiple people, divide the total by the number of diners.</p>
            <p>This tip calculator handles all of that instantly. Enter your bill amount, choose a tip percentage (or use the preset buttons for 15%, 18%, 20%, 22%, or 25%), and optionally set the number of people to split between. The calculator shows the tip amount, total bill, and per-person breakdown in real time.</p>

            <h2>How Much to Tip: US Tipping Standards</h2>
            <p>In the United States, tipping is customary for most service industries. The standard tip at a <strong>sit-down restaurant</strong> is 15–20% of the pre-tax bill, with 20% increasingly considered the baseline for satisfactory service. For <strong>exceptional service</strong>, tips of 22–25% or more are common. At counter-service restaurants, cafes, and takeout spots, tipping is optional but appreciated — $1–2 or 10–15% is typical.</p>
            <p>Beyond restaurants, tipping norms vary by service type. Food delivery drivers, hairstylists, taxi and rideshare drivers, and bartenders generally receive 15–20%. Hotel housekeepers are typically tipped $2–5 per night, and valets receive $2–5 when returning your car. Consult the tipping guide table above for a comprehensive breakdown by service category.</p>

            <h2>Pre-Tax vs. Post-Tax Tipping</h2>
            <p>Etiquette experts recommend calculating your tip on the <strong>pre-tax subtotal</strong> rather than the post-tax total. Sales tax is owed to the government and doesn't reflect the quality of service. On a $100 meal with 8% sales tax, a 20% tip on the pre-tax amount is $20, while tipping on the $108 total would be $21.60. The difference is small, but it adds up over time. This calculator lets you toggle pre-tax tipping and enter your pre-tax subtotal separately for the most accurate calculation.</p>

            <h2>Splitting the Bill with a Group</h2>
            <p>When dining with a group, the easiest approach is to calculate the tip on the <strong>entire bill</strong> and then divide everything evenly. For example, a $200 bill with a 20% tip ($40) totals $240, which splits to $60 per person in a group of four. If diners ordered items at very different price points, consider splitting proportionally — but for simplicity, even splits are the most common approach. This calculator lets you enter any number of people and instantly shows the per-person tip and total.</p>

            <h2>Round Up: A Simple Way to Tip More</h2>
            <p>The <strong>round-up</strong> feature rounds your total bill to the nearest whole dollar after adding the tip. This makes payment easier (no coins to deal with) and often adds a few extra cents to the tip. For example, if your bill is $47.50 and a 20% tip brings the total to $57.00, there's nothing to round. But if the total comes to $56.73, rounding up to $57.00 adds $0.27 to the tip — a painless way to be slightly more generous.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <div class="faq-section">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much should I tip at a restaurant?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">The standard tip at a sit-down restaurant in the United States is 15–20% of the pre-tax bill. For excellent service, 20–25% is common. At a buffet or counter-service restaurant, 10% is typical. Always tip on the pre-tax subtotal rather than the total that includes sales tax for the most accurate gratuity calculation.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Should I tip on the pre-tax or post-tax amount?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Etiquette experts recommend tipping on the pre-tax subtotal. Sales tax is money owed to the government, not part of the service you received. For example, on a $100 meal with 8% tax, a 20% tip should be $20 (based on $100), not $21.60 (based on $108). That said, tipping on the post-tax total is also common and results in only a slightly higher tip.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I calculate a tip without a calculator?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">For a quick 20% tip, move the decimal point one place to the left (that gives you 10%) and double it. For example, on a $65 bill: 10% is $6.50, so 20% is $13. For 15%, calculate 10% and add half of that: $6.50 + $3.25 = $9.75. For 25%, calculate 10% and multiply by 2.5, or just add a quarter of the bill.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much should I tip for delivery?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">For food delivery, tip 15–20% of the order total, with a minimum of $3–5 for small orders. In bad weather or if the driver traveled a long distance, consider tipping more. For grocery delivery, 15–20% is standard, with a $5 minimum. Many delivery apps allow you to adjust the tip after delivery based on the service quality.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do I need to tip if a service charge or gratuity is already included?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">If a service charge or automatic gratuity is already included in the bill (common for large parties of 6+), you generally do not need to tip extra. However, check whether the service charge actually goes to the server — some restaurants keep it as a fee. If the included gratuity is below 18%, you may want to add a small additional tip for great service.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I split a tip evenly among a group?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">To split a tip evenly, first calculate the total tip on the entire bill, then divide by the number of people. For example, a $200 bill with a 20% tip is $40 in gratuity. Split among 4 people, that's $10 each in tip, or $60 each for the total ($200 + $40 = $240 ÷ 4). This calculator handles the math automatically — just enter the number of people.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the difference between a tip and a gratuity?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">A tip and a gratuity are essentially the same thing — both refer to extra money given to a service worker beyond the bill amount. However, 'gratuity' is sometimes used specifically for mandatory or automatic charges added to bills for large parties, while 'tip' usually refers to a voluntary amount. In everyday use, the terms are interchangeable.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much should I tip at a hair salon or barbershop?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">The standard tip at a hair salon or barbershop is 15–20% of the service cost. For a simple haircut, 15–20% is appropriate. For more complex services like coloring, highlights, or styling, 20% or more is customary. If multiple people work on your hair (e.g., a colorist and a stylist), tip each person separately based on their portion of the service.</div>
            </div>
        </div>

